  labs(title = "No information from X at all")

two sample t.test \(\bar{x}_{City Hotel} - \bar{x}_{Resort Hotel}\)

t.test(adr ~ hotel, data = Hotel_bookings, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  adr by hotel
## t = 33.576, df = 119388, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   9.747278 10.955794
## sample estimates:
##   mean in group City Hotel mean in group Resort Hotel 
##                  105.30447                   94.95293

Because the p-value < 2.2e-16, we are going to: - Reject the null hypothesis - There is evidence that the hotel type is related to the price - There is an association between price and hotel type - We can use the hotel type to predict price!

95% CI

Linear Regression

Does the hotel price affect the number of staying days in weekdays?

City_price_mean <- mean(Hotel_bookings$adr[Hotel_bookings$hotel == "City Hotel"])
Hotel_bookings %>% 
  filter(hotel == "City Hotel") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = 1, y = adr)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2) +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = City_price_mean, color = "Null model (y-bar)")) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,2)) +
  labs(title = "No information from X at all")

posn_j <- position_jitter(seed = 136)

Hotel_bookings %>% 
  filter(hotel == "City Hotel") %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = stays_in_week_nights, y = adr)) +
  geom_point(position = posn_j, shape = ".", alpha = 0.25) +
  # stat_summary(fun.data = mean_sdl, 
               #fun.args = list(mult = 1), col = "red") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  NULL
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

- the null hypothesis fail to reject since null hypothesis very close to zero(i.e. the null model) - There is no association between price and the number of stay days
